1. Sniffer Operation
    

- Sniffer must work with the type of network interface and supported by your OS 
    
- Sniffers look only at the traffic passing through the network interface adapter on the machine where the application is resident. If you need to monitor from another machine, you’ll need an agent. 
    
- You can read the traffic on the network segment upon which your computer resides 
    
- Typical traffic will include Unicast & Broadcast packets 
    



1. Components of a Sniffer
    

- Hardware 
    
    - NIC is a definite requirement 
    - Different types (Wired, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, etc…
##### Capture Driver 
    
    - Captures the network traffic from the Ethernet connection 
        
    - Filters out the information that you don’t want and then stores the filtered traffic information in a buffer 
        

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
    

- Buffer 
    
    - Dynamic area of RAM that holds specified data.  
    - Methods of storing captured data 
        
        - Stored until the buffer is full with information 
        - Round-robin method 
            
- Decoder
    - Interprets binary information and then displays it in a readable format 
        
- Packet Analysis 
    
    - Sniffers usually provide real-time analysis of captured packets. But can also read previous captures. 
    - If we are placing the network sniffer on the computer, we will only get traffic from that machine. If we are monitoring a switch, it would be connected to a cable connected to a switch. 

In late 1990s, we can use COAX cable, which has : 
1. core
2. insulator
3. wire mesh 


There used to be a **Vampire Tap**, where the idea is for it to be attached to the mesh. You can not do that with CAT-5 or CAT-6 cables.

4. Placement of a Sniffer
    

- A sniffer can be implemented anywhere in a network 
    
- Sniffer is ideally placed in a location where only the required data will be captured 
    
- Sniffers are normally placed on: 
    
    - Computers 
        
    - Cable connections 
        
    - Routers 
        
    - Network segments connected to the Internet 
        
    - Network segments connected to servers

6. Snort
    

- Can be used as a packet sniffer like tcpdump, a packet logger (useful for network traffic debugging, etc), or as a full-blown network Intrusion Detection/Prevention System (IDS/IPS). 
One of the first intrusion detection systems. CISCO purchased SourceFire, and now owns **snort**. It is an IPS now too!
- In IDS mode, the program will monitor network traffic and analyze it against a rule set defined by the user. The program can then perform a specific action based on what has been identified.  
    
- One of the common methods being a block, or a drop, placed on the suspicious packet(s). At this point it starts to become an IPS. 
    

7. Snort
    

- The five basic rule types in Snort are: 
    
    - Alert rules: Snort generates an alert when a suspicious packet is detected. One of the first! You can set a ping alert.
    - Block rules: Snort blocks the suspicious packet and all subsequent packets in the network flow. Part of the Intrusion Prevention System.
    - Drop rules: Snort drops the packet as soon as the alert is generated.  Part of the Intrusion Prevention System.
    - Logging rules: Snort logs the packet as soon as the alert is generated. 
    - Pass rules: Snort ignores the suspicious packet and marks it as passed.

## Detecting a Sniffer
    

- Since sniffer technology is passive it can be difficult to detect sniffers 
- The best defense for sniffers is to never let one be installed into your network. 
Scenario : 

Attacker connects a laptop to a switch port. He runs discovery tools to discover topography. 1-3 is passive, 4-6 is attacking. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

5. Detecting a Sniffer
    

- 1. Tips:
        

- - Restrict the physical access to the network media to ensure that a packet sniffer cannot be installed.  
        
    - Use end-to-end encryption to protect confidential information.  
    - Permanently add the MAC address of the gateway to the ARP cache.  
    - Use static IP addresses and ARP tables to prevent attackers from adding the spoofed ARP entries for machines in the network.  
    - Turn off network identification broadcasts and if possible restrict the network to authorized users in order to protect the network from being discovered with sniffing tools.  

BetterCAP is able to capture packets. If the connection is encrypted, it can only see the packet itself, not the contenrs. 

6. Detecting a Sniffer
    

- 1. Ping Method
        
        To detect a sniffer on a network, identify the system on the network running in promiscuous mode. The ping method is useful in detecting a system that runs in promiscuous mode, which in turns helps to detect sniffers installed on the network.
        
        Just send a ping request to the suspected machine with its IP address and incorrect MAC address. The adapter will reject it as the MAC address does not match, whereas the suspect machine running the sniffer responds to it, as it does not reject packets with a different MAC address. Thus, this response will identify the sniffer in the network.
        

7. Detecting a Sniffer
    

- 1. Reverse-DNS Method
        
        
        IP address to name, instead of naming an ip address . 
        
        
        The reverse DNS lookup is the opposite of the DNS lookup method. Sniffers using reverse DNS lookup increase network traffic. This increase in network traffic can be an indication of the presence of a sniffer on the network.
        
        Users can perform a reverse DNS lookup remotely or locally. Monitor the organization’s DNS server to identify incoming reverse DNS lookups. The method sending ICMP requests to a non-existing IP address can also monitor reverse DNS lookups. The computer performing the reverse DNS lookup would respond to the ping, thus identifying it as hosting a sniffer.
        

8. Detecting a Sniffer
    

- 1. ARP Method
        
        This technique sends a non-broadcast ARP to all the nodes in the network. The node that runs in promiscuous mode on the network will cache the local ARP address. Then it will broadcast a ping message on the network with the local IP address but a different MAC address. In this case, only the node that has the MAC address (cached earlier) will be able to respond to your broadcast ping request.
        
        A machine in promiscuous mode replies to the ping message as it has incorrect information about the host that is sending ping request in its cache; the rest of the machines will send ARP probe to identify the source of the ping request. This will detect the node on which the sniffer is running.
        

9. Summary
    

- A sniffer, or packet sniffer, is an application that monitors, filters, and captures data packets transferred over a network 
    
- The components of a sniffer are hardware, capture driver, buffer, decoder, and packet analysis 
    
- Sniffers need to be placed where they will get the smallest aggregate network traffic 
    

10. Summary (continued)
    

- Sniffers change the NIC operation mode to promiscuous mode 
    
- Wireshark, Tcpdump/Windump, and Snort are all modern packet sniffers 
    
- Fluke Networks Protocol Analyzers are examples of commercial packet sniffers 
    

11. Summary (continued)
    

- Several tools exist, or have existed, to detect a sniffer 
    
- All tools for protecting your network from a packet sniffer involve some level of encryption
